# Git conventions

## Commit message format (Conventional Commits)

```
<type>(<optional scope>): <imperative, lowercase summary>

[optional body explaining WHY, not WHAT]

[optional footer: Breaking change / Closes #issue]
```

Types:
| Type | When to use |
|---|---|
| `feat` | New user-facing feature |
| `fix` | Bug fix |
| `chore` | Dependency bump, config, tooling |
| `docs` | Documentation only |
| `refactor` | Internal code restructure, no behavior change |
| `style` | Formatting, lint, CSS only |
| `test` | Add or fix tests |
| `perf` | Performance improvement |

Examples:
```
feat(auth): add email verification flow with Supabase trigger
fix(order): prevent invalid state transition from paid -> draft
chore: upgrade supabase-js to 2.106
docs(schema): document RLS policy matrix
```

## Branch naming

```
feature/<ticket-or-slug>   e.g. feature/seller-listing-form
fix/<slug>                 e.g. fix/middleware-redirect-loop
chore/<slug>               e.g. chore/upgrade-supabase
release/vX.Y.Z
```

## Safe git operations

- **NEVER** `git push --force` on `main`/`master`.
- **NEVER** commit `.env`, `.env.local`, or any file containing real API keys.
- Use `git add -p` for selective staging on large refactors.
- Squash WIP commits before merging to `main`.

## Files that must NOT be committed

```
.env
.env.local
.env.*.local
supabase/.branches
supabase/.temp
node_modules/
.next/
```

These are all in `.gitignore`. Always verify with `git status` before committing.

## Recommended workflow

```powershell
# Check what will be committed
git status
git diff --cached

# Stage and commit
git add -A
git commit -m "feat(auth): implement signup/signin server actions"

# Push feature branch (NOT force-push to main)
git push origin feature/auth-flow
```

## When writing commit messages as an AI agent

1. Run `git diff --cached` first to see exact changes.
2. Summarize the **why** (business reason), not just the **what**.
3. Keep the subject line ≤ 72 chars.
4. Reference related issues with `Closes #N` if applicable.
